Types of Directory in Linux
In Linux, directories are used to organize files and system data. Different types of directories serve different purposes in the file system.

1. Root Directory (/)      
	• The top-most directory in Linux
	• Represented by /
	• All Other directories start from root
Example:
/

2. Home Directory (~)
	• Personal directory for each user
	• Stores user files, documents, downloads, etc.
	• Represented by ~
Example:
/home/student

3. Parent Directory
	• The directory that contains another directory
	• Represented by ..
Example:
/home/student/Documents
Here, student is the parent directory of Documents

4. Child Directory
	• A directory inside another directory
Example:
Documents/Notes
Here, Notes is the child directory of Documents

5. Current Directory
	• The directory you are currently working in
	• Represented by    .
Ex:
pwd

6. Subdirectory (Nested Directory)
	• A directory inside another directory, at any level
Example:
/home/student/Documents/Linux/Notes

7. System Directories
Important directories used by the Linux system:
Directory	Purpose
/bin	Essential user commands
/sbin	System administration commands
/etc	Configuration files
/lib	System libraries
/boot	Boot loader files
/dev	Device files
/proc	Process information
/tmp	Temporary files
/var	Variable data (logs, mail)

8. Working Directory
	The directory where commands are executed
	Same as current directory
	
	pwd
	
	
